Grid plot¶

When exploring multi-dimensional data, a useful approach is to draw multiple instances of the same plot on different subsets of your dataset. It allows you to quickly extract a large amount of information about a complex dataset.

Refs: https://seaborn.pydata.org/tutorial/axis_grids.html

In [1]:
#Importing 
import seaborn as sns 
%matplotlib inline
In [2]:
#loading 'iris' dataset 
iris = sns.load_dataset('iris')
iris.head()
Out[2]:
sepal_length sepal_width petal_length petal_width species
0 5.1 3.5 1.4 0.2 setosa
1 4.9 3.0 1.4 0.2 setosa
2 4.7 3.2 1.3 0.2 setosa

PairGrid¶

Subplot grid for plotting pairwise relationships in a dataset.

  • PairGrid enables you to quickly draw a grid of small subplots using the same plot type to visualize data in each.
  • In a PairGrid, each row and column is assigned to a different variable, so the resulting plot shows each pairwise relationship in the dataset.
In [5]:
#Just create the grid 
sns.PairGrid(iris)
Out[5]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x7fe021fd3d60>
In [7]:
#map the plot on the grid using scatterplot  

g = sns.PairGrid(iris)
g.map(sns.scatterplot)
Out[7]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x7fe00069ad30>
In [10]:
#diagonally histplot() and at others scatterplot() 
g = sns.PairGrid(iris)
g.map_diag(sns.histplot)
g.map_offdiag(sns.scatterplot)
Out[10]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x7fe02244da90>
In [12]:
#Different type of plot on the grid 
g = sns.PairGrid(iris)
g.map_upper(sns.scatterplot) #scatterplot on the upper 
g.map_lower(sns.kdeplot)     # kdeplot on the lower 
g.map_diag(sns.histplot)    # histogram on the diagonal
Out[12]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x7fdff026b2e0>

Pairplot¶

PairGrid is flexible, but to take a quick look at a dataset, it can be easier to use 'pairplot()'.

In [12]:
#Creating pairplot with 'iris' dataset 
sns.pairplot(iris)
Out[12]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x7fe7c01f2040>
In [17]:
#Creating pairplot with 'iris' dataset and hut set to species 
#sns.pairplot(iris,palette='rainbow',hue='species',height=3,diag_kind='kde')
sns.pairplot(iris, hue='species',height=3,diag_kind='kde')
Out[17]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x7fe026c58850>

Facet grid¶

  • Facet grid is a generic grid creating approach when you want to use features to create the grid.
  • The FacetGrid class is useful when you want to visualize the distribution of a variable or the relationship between multiple variables separately within subsets of your dataset.
  • A FacetGrid can be drawn with up to three dimensions: row, col, and hue.
In [22]:
#load tips dataset 
tips = sns.load_dataset('tips')
tips.head()
Out[22]:
total_bill tip sex smoker day time size
0 16.99 1.01 Female No Sun Dinner 2
1 10.34 1.66 Male No Sun Dinner 3
2 21.01 3.50 Male No Sun Dinner 3
3 23.68 3.31 Male No Sun Dinner 2
4 24.59 3.61 Female No Sun Dinner 4
In [23]:
#Create a facetgrid 
#two rows: dinner and lunch and two columns for smoker and non-smoker 
#sns.FacetGrid(tips,row='time',col='smoker') 
sns.FacetGrid(tips,row='time',col='smoker')
Out[23]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x7fe027c952e0>
In [27]:
#Create a facetgrid 
g = sns.FacetGrid(tips,row='time',col='smoker')
g.map(sns.histplot,'tip')
Out[27]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x7fe027f397f0>
In [31]:
#Create a facetgrid with hue set 
# g = sns.FacetGrid(tips,row='time',col='smoker', hue='sex')
# g.map(sns.scatterplot,'total_bill','tip',alpha=0.8)
# g.add_legend()

g= sns.FacetGrid(tips,row='time',col='smoker',hue='sex')
g.map(sns.scatterplot,'total_bill','tip',alpha=0.8)
g.add_legend()

Joinpot¶

It draws a plot of two variables with bivariate and univariate graphs.

In [32]:
#Jointplot example 
sns.jointplot(data=tips,x='total_bill',y='tip')
Out[32]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.JointGrid at 0x7fdfc050b460>

The upper one (histogram) is similar like the below histplot() for total_bill

In [33]:
sns.histplot(tips['total_bill'])

The right (histogram) one is similar like the below histplot() for tip
